  <h1>Dealing with Trucking Insurance Companies</h1>
  <p class="byline">By our editorial team. Reviewed May 2026.</p>

  <p>The carrier's insurance company is not your friend. The adjuster's job is to close the claim for as little money as the file will tolerate. That is not a moral failing on the adjuster's part; it's how the claims industry is organized. Knowing the standard plays lets you respond to them on something closer to even ground.</p>

  <h2>What happens in the first 30 days</h2>
  <p>Within hours or days of the crash, the carrier's insurer will:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Open a claim file</strong> and assign an adjuster.</li>
    <li><strong>Send an investigator</strong> to the scene if injuries or severity warrant it. The investigator photographs the scene, interviews witnesses, and may interview you if you'll allow it.</li>
    <li><strong>Pull the police report</strong> and the driver's records.</li>
    <li><strong>Reach out to you</strong> &mdash; often with sympathy, an offer to handle your medical bills, and a request for a recorded statement.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If you take only one piece of advice from this guide: <strong>do not give a recorded statement</strong> to the carrier's insurer without an attorney present. The statement will be used to lock you into a story that benefits the defense, will be parsed for any inconsistency with later testimony, and is almost never necessary or helpful to your case.</p>

  <h2>The early offer</h2>
  <p>Often within 2&ndash;6 weeks the adjuster will offer "settlement" of some kind. The early-offer ranges vary:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Property damage only.</strong> Reasonable cars are valued in line with actual cash value; trucks may quibble more. Sign a property-damage-only release after reading every word &mdash; it should release property claims only, not personal injury claims.</li>
    <li><strong>"Nuisance value" injury settlement.</strong> A few thousand to ~$15,000 for minor injuries, offered to close the file before treatment is complete. Almost always too low for anything that involved an ER visit or imaging.</li>
    <li><strong>Mid-treatment offer.</strong> Larger numbers offered while you're still in PT or recovery. These are calibrated to your <em>current</em> bills, not to your eventual total medical or future costs. Reject these and wait for MMI.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Maximum medical improvement (MMI)</h2>
  <p>MMI is the point where your condition has stabilized &mdash; either fully healed or as healed as you're going to get. <strong>You do not settle an injury case before MMI.</strong> Reasons:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>You don't know your total medical cost until treatment is complete.</li>
    <li>You don't know whether you have permanent impairment or future medical needs.</li>
    <li>A release signed pre-MMI cannot be reopened if your condition worsens.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For most crash injuries MMI is reached within 6&ndash;18 months. For surgical cases or TBI, it can be 18&ndash;36 months. Resist the pressure to settle "by the end of the year" or "before treatment is complete." That pressure is the insurer's tool, not your friend.</p>

  <h2>Reservation-of-rights letters</h2>
  <p>If the carrier suspects coverage issues &mdash; the driver was off-policy, the truck wasn't owned by the named insured, the use was outside the policy &mdash; you may receive (or your attorney may receive) a reservation-of-rights letter. This means the insurer is investigating coverage and reserves the right to deny. It does not mean the claim is dead; it means there's a coverage layer that requires its own analysis.</p>
  <p>Reservation-of-rights letters complicate settlement timing. They are normal in commercial trucking cases. Don't panic; do get the letter to an attorney.</p>

  <h2>Adjuster tactics to recognize</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>"Send me your medical bills directly."</strong> Don't. Send them to your attorney. Adjusters use direct submission to verify treatment dates and amounts and then build defenses to specific charges. Have your attorney submit a curated package.</li>
    <li><strong>"We need a recorded statement before we can move forward."</strong> They don't. They can move forward without one.</li>
    <li><strong>"You don't need a lawyer; we'll handle this fairly."</strong> Adjusters genuinely believe they're being fair. The market data is unambiguous that represented plaintiffs net more.</li>
    <li><strong>"This is our final offer."</strong> It almost never is. The final offer comes after the suit is filed, discovery is done, and a mediator is in the room.</li>
    <li><strong>Authority limits.</strong> Each adjuster has a settlement authority cap. Big cases require supervisor approval and then committee approval. If you're at the supervisor level and getting "no," you're often one filed complaint away from a more meaningful settlement conversation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to settle vs. when to file</h2>
  <p>Settle pre-suit when:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Liability is undisputed.</li>
    <li>Treatment is complete and damages are well-documented.</li>
    <li>The offer is in or above your attorney's expected range.</li>
    <li>You have settlement-fatigue and the value of certainty outweighs the upside of trial.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>File suit when:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The offer is materially below your attorney's expected range.</li>
    <li>Liability is contested and you need discovery to develop the case.</li>
    <li>The carrier won't engage seriously without litigation pressure.</li>
    <li>Statute-of-limitations pressure forces filing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Subrogation and liens</h2>
  <p>The number you settle for is not the number you keep. From your gross settlement, deductions include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Attorney's contingent fee</strong> (typically 33% pre-suit or 40% if filed).</li>
    <li><strong>Case costs</strong> (filing fees, deposition costs, expert fees, medical record charges).</li>
    <li><strong>Subrogation</strong> &mdash; your health insurer, ERISA plan, or auto med-pay carrier recoups what it spent on your treatment.</li>
    <li><strong>Medicare / Medicaid liens.</strong> Federal liens come off the top and are aggressively enforced.</li>
    <li><strong>Workers' comp liens</strong> if you had a comp claim arising from the same crash.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Your attorney negotiates lien reductions; it's a substantial part of plaintiff-side PI work. Net recovery is typically 50&ndash;65% of gross settlement after fees, costs, and liens are paid, sometimes more, sometimes less.</p>

  <p>For the formula behind the settlement amount, see <a href="/methodology">methodology</a>. For how comparative fault affects what's on the table, see <a href="/guides/comparative-fault-truck-accidents">our comparative fault guide</a>.</p>
